## Rules

### TEST-001: Table-Driven Tests
severity: ERROR
scope: all Go test functions
rule: Tests with multiple input scenarios MUST use table-driven tests with a slice of anonymous structs. Each test case MUST have a descriptive `name` field. Test functions MUST use `t.Run(tc.name, ...)`.
threshold: min_coverage_pct=70, max_test_file_lines=400
example_correct: |
  tests := []struct {
      name  string
      input string
      want  string
  }{
      {"empty input", "", "error"},
      {"valid input", "abc", "ok"},
  }
  for _, tc := range tests {
      t.Run(tc.name, func(t *testing.T) { ... })
  }
example_incorrect: |
  func TestProcess1(t *testing.T) { ... }
  func TestProcess2(t *testing.T) { ... }  // not table-driven

### TEST-002: Test Helpers
severity: ERROR
scope: all Go test files
rule: Test helper functions MUST call `t.Helper()` as their first statement. Test assertions MUST use `t.Errorf` not `t.Fatalf` unless the test cannot continue. Test packages MUST use the `_test` suffix.
threshold: min_coverage_pct=70
example_correct: |
  func assertNoError(t *testing.T, err error) {
      t.Helper()
      if err != nil { t.Errorf("unexpected error: %v", err) }
  }
example_incorrect: |
  func checkErr(t *testing.T, err error) {
      // missing t.Helper() — test line numbers will be wrong
  }
